\par }{\f5 Kermit for Windows requires any of the existing flavors of MS Windows Version 3.1.  These flavors include MS Windows, MS Windows for Workgroups, MS Windows 95, and MS
 Windows NT.  Only the Intel variation of Windows NT is supported at this time.  Although Windows95 and Windows NT will run 16 bit applications (i. e., the 16-bit version of Kermit for Windows), it is preferable to run the 32-bit version.
\par 
\par Kermit for Windows supports both standard asynchronous (modem style) and TCP/IP (Telnet style) communications.
\par 
\par For asynchronous connectivity, Kermit for Windows relies upon the serial port drivers included with Windows.  I have been told that aftermarket serial drivers f
or Windows work fine, but have not personally tested this.  Support for Hayes compatible modems is also provided when using Asynchronous communications.
\par 
\par For TCP/IP connectivity, Kermit for Windows relies upon the WinSock library.  Most TCP/IP software vendors now support the WinSock API, so this should not be much of a constraint.  In theory all WinSock implementations should be compatible, but I have onl
y tested the Microsoft WinSock libraries.  Microsoft includes a WinSock library with Windows 95 and Win
dows NT.  They have also just released a free version of WinSock for Windows for Workgroups.  This free WinSock implementation can be downloaded from the Microsoft Software Library on CompuServe or from ftp.microsoft.com on the Internet.
\par 
\par The memory and hard disk requirements of Kermit for Windows are extremely small and should almost never be a problem.
\par 
\par }{\b\f5 Installation/Setup}{\f5 
\par Installation is similar to most applications distributed via online services.  Kermit for Windows is distributed as an executable archive (self extracting zip file).  After downloading the distribution file to your local 
system, just execute it.  The compressed files will be expanded and the setup routine will be invoked automatically.
\par 
\par If you are going to use the TCP/IP protocol support, you must separately acquire and install a Version 1.1 or greater WinSock library (Windows 95/NT include this library).
\par 
\par Also, if you want to use VBScript scripting, you must separately install Microsoft's VBScript engine.  The easiest way to do this is to install MS Internet Explorer Version 3.0.  This product can be downloaded for 
free from Microsoft's web site www.microsoft.com.  Note that currently there is only a 32-bit version of the VBScript Engine; therefore, there is no scripting support in 16-bit Kermit.
\par 
\par }{\b\f5 Note}{\f5 :  Users are encouraged to review the enclosed ASCII text file README.TXT for late breaking information on the specific release.
