\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\tx7200\tqdec\tx9360 {\i\f5 Baud Rate
\par }{\f5 
Enter the baud rate that you wish to use to communicate with the remote system or the speed your modem requires.  Although you are allowed to enter any value, only 300, 1200, 2400, 4800, 9600, 19200, 38400, and 57600 should be used.  Additionally, Windows
 will not support the higher baud rates with some types of serial port hardware.
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Word Length
\par }{\f5 Also known as data bits.  Usually 8, but occasionally 7.  The administrator of the system you are trying to connect with should be able to give you this information.
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Parity
\par }{\f5 Normally none, but again the administrator of the remote system should be able to supply this information.  Note that N=None, E=Even, O=Odd, M=Mark, S=Space.
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Stop Bits
\par }{\f5 Number of stops bits required by the remote system.  Almost always 1.
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Handshake
\par }{\f5 Kermit for Windows supports two types of "flow control".  Xon/Xoff uses control characters to prevent buffer overruns.  RTS/CTS uses two
 specific lines (wires) on the serial port to achieve the same effect.  Which option is appropriate depends on your modem configuration and remote system requirements.
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Port
\par }{\f5 Kermit for Windows support COM ports 1 through 4 (if available).  Although all 4 selections are always shown, your computer probably doesn't have all four.  Be sure to choose a port that exists and is available and properly configured under Windows.

\par }\pard \nowidctlpar {\f5 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\tx7200\tqdec\tx9360 {\b\f5\fs24\ul TCP/IP
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar {\f5 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\tx7200\tqdec\tx9360 {\i\f5 Host
\par }{\f5 Enter the Internet host name you wish to connect to (like microsoft.com) or the Internet address to connect to (like 129.193.208.56). 
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Port
\par }{\f5 Enter the name or number of the TCP/IP service to use.  This entry is almost always telnet and should only be changed if you are sure you understand the use of non-standard ports. 
\par 
\par NOTE: although it is called a "port", this is nothing like a "serial port".  A TCP/IP port has no connector on the back of your PC, it is a logical port. 
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Terminal
\par }{\f5 Most Telnet host servers have the ability to read the terminal type of the users machine at connec
tion time.  To enable this feature, you must specify the name of the terminal type you wish to provide to the host.  Kermit for Windows will provide this name to the host if it requests it. 
\par 
\par NOTE: this entry does NOT determine the type of emulation that Kermit for Windows will perform (that is determined by the Emulation setting in the Session Configuration Dialog).  This entry should correspond to a name that your host understands and will a
ssociate with the type of emulation you have already chosen in the Session Configuration Dialog. 
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Send CR LF for End of Line
\par }{\f5 If you are attempting to talk to a non-standard telnet service, the host may require both a CR and LF control code at the end of every input line.  If you don't understand this option, you probably don't want to use it. 
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Suppress Negotiation
\par }{\f5 The Telnet protocol requires that the client and host "negotiate" certain configuration settings at startup.  In rare cases you may want to disable this negotiation. 
