\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\tx7200\tqdec\tx9360 {\i\f5 Packet Size
\par }{\f5 Size of data packets in bytes desired for send and receive.
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Timeout
\par }{\f5 Number of seconds to wait before assuming a lost packet for send and receive.
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Retry Limit
\par }{\f5 Maximum number of retries before aborting protocol.
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Block Check
\par }{\f5 Kermit provides three different error detection block check types.  Block Check Type 1 is the least reliable and Block Check Type 3 is the most reliable.
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Debug
\par }{\f5 Select debugging options as desired.  Packet option will display packets sent/received.  State option will show state of protocol engine at various points.  Other is undefined.
\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Options
\par }{\f5 
Check the appropriate boxes  for advanced Kermit protocol functions.  Attrib will allow file information attributes to be used.  L. Pkts will allow packet sizes up to 1000 bytes.  Windows will allow the sliding windows extension to be used (Super Kermit).

\par 
\par }{\i\f5 Packets...
\par }{\f5 This button invokes a nested dialog that allows special customization of various Kermit packet characters.  It is not normally needed.
\par 
